c or persistent disease that might change the course of treatment [Data: Entity (18); Relationship (38)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Advanced and metastatic disease management forms a highly specialized protocol subset.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"As disease progresses to a metastatic state—such as metachronous oligometastatic castration-sensitive prostate cancer (M1 CSPC, PROS-13 and PROS-15) and castration-resistant prostate cancer (M1 CRPC, PROS-17)—the protocol community branches into detailed workup and treatment stages specific to high-risk, high-volume, or resistant disease. Diagnostic workup for metastases is a recurring step, reflecting the protocols' emphasis on accurate staging to direct systemic and locoregional therapies appropriately [Data: Entities (37, 46, 63); Relationships (108, 140, 180)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Protocols are interlinked through decision-point relationships.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"Each protocol page is connected to the next by decision points—such as patient survival, recurrence evidence, or risk stratification—that act as triggers for escalation or new rounds of diagnosis and therapy. For example, the detection of PSA persistence/recurrence after radical prostatectomy directs the application of PROS-9, while signs of radiation therapy failure prompt the use of PROS-10. This interconnection ensures a seamless transition between protocols and supports a holistic patient journey throughout the disease course [Data: Relationships (387, 463, 0, 427, 38)].\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"summary\": \"Continuous escalation and adaptation are hallmarks of the guideline structure.\",\n      \"explanation\": \"The NCCN protocol community reflects continuous clinical escalation, with each recurrence or failure leading to more intensive investigations and targeted treatments. Tracking patient history through successive protocol pages supports personalized medicine and optimizes outcomes by responding dynamically 